Python Working with JSON¶

JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a lightweight data interchange format that is easy for humans to read and write.

It is also easy for machines to parse and generate.

JSON represents data in a structured way, using key-value pairs similar to dictionaries in Python.

Example JSON Format:

# Example JSON string representing a book
book_json = '{"title": "Animal Farm", "author": "George Orwell", "year": 1945, "genre": "Political Satire"}'

Parsing JSON to Python¶

First, import the json module. Then use loads method. It converts to python dictionary.

import json

# Example JSON string representing a book
book_json = '{"title": "Animal Farm", "author": "George Orwell", "year": 1945, "genre": "Political Satire"}'

# Parse JSON string to Python dictionary
book_dict = json.loads(book_json)

# Accessing data from the dictionary
print("Title:", book_dict["title"])      # Output: Animal Farm
print("Author:", book_dict["author"])    # Output: George Orwell
print("Year:", book_dict["year"])        # Output: 1945
print("Genre:", book_dict["genre"])      # Output: Political Satire

Title: Animal Farm
Author: George Orwell
Year: 1945
Genre: Political Satire

Converting Python to JSON¶

Let’s convert a Python dictionary representing a movie to a JSON string. we use dumps method to conver json.

import json

# Example Python dictionary for a movie
movie_dict = {
    "title": "Inception",
    "director": "Christopher Nolan",
    "year": 2010,
    "cast": ["Leonardo DiCaprio", "Joseph Gordon-Levitt", "Elliot Page"]
}

# Convert Python dictionary to JSON string
movie_json = json.dumps(movie_dict)

# Output the JSON string
print(movie_json)

{"title": "Inception", "director": "Christopher Nolan", "year": 2010, "cast": ["Leonardo DiCaprio", "Joseph Gordon-Levitt", "Elliot Page"]}

Python Regular Expressions (RegEx)¶

A RegEx, or Regular Expression, is a sequence of characters that forms a search pattern.

To start using regular expressions in Python, you first need to import the re module.

import re

A simple example to check if a string starts with "The" and ends with "Spain".

txt = "The rain in Spain"
x = re.search("^The.*Spain$", txt)

if x:
    print("Match found!")
else:
    print("No match.")

Match found!

RegEx Functions¶

The re module offers several functions to work with RegEx patterns:

findall: Returns a list of all matches in the string

search: Returns a Match object if there is a match

split: Splits the string at each match

sub: Replaces matches with the specified string

txt = "The rain in Spain"
matches = re.findall("ai", txt)
print("Matches found:", matches)  # Output: ['ai', 'ai']

Matches found: ['ai', 'ai']

findall

xt = "The rain in Spain"
matches = re.findall("Portugal", txt)
print("Matches found:", matches)  # Output: []

Matches found: []

search

txt = "The rain in Spain"
match = re.search("a", txt)
print(match)

if match:
    print("The first 'a' character is located in position:", match.start())

<re.Match object; span=(5, 6), match='a'>
The first 'a' character is located in position: 5

txt = "The rain in Spain"
match = re.search("\s", txt)

if match:
    print("The first white-space character is located in position:", match.start())

The first white-space character is located in position: 3

split

txt = "The rain in Spain"
result = re.split("\s", txt)
print("Split result:", result)  # Output: ['The', 'rain', 'in', 'Spain']

Split result: ['The', 'rain', 'in', 'Spain']

Alternative way with pure Python:

txt = "The rain in Spain"
result = txt.split()
print("Split result with spaces (pure Python):", result)  # Output: ['The', 'rain', 'in', 'Spain']

Split result with spaces (pure Python): ['The', 'rain', 'in', 'Spain']

sub

sub() function replaces matches with a specified string.

txt = "The rain in Spain"
result = re.sub("\s", "9", txt)
print("Substituted result:", result)  # Output: The9rain9in9Spain

Substituted result: The9rain9in9Spain

match

A Match Object contains information about the search result. If no match is found, None is returned instead.

txt = "The rain in Spain"
match = re.search("ai", txt)

if match:
    print("Match object:", match)

Match object: <re.Match object; span=(5, 7), match='ai'>

Accessing Match Object Properties:

span(): Returns a tuple containing the start and end positions of the match.

string: Returns the original string.

group(): Returns the part of the string where there was a match.

Aşağıdaki kod bloğu, txt değişkenindeki metinde "S" harfiyle başlayan ve ardından gelen kelimeyi arar. Örneğin:

txt = "The rain in Spain"
match = re.search(r"\bS\w+", txt)

if match:
    print("Match span:", match.span())        # Output: (12, 17)
    print("Original string:", match.string)    # Output: The rain in Spain
    print("Matched text:", match.group())      # Output: Spain

Match span: (12, 17)
Original string: The rain in Spain
Matched text: Spain

r"\bS\w+": Bu, aramak istediğiniz deseni temsil eden bir regular expression (regüler ifade) dizesidir. Bu ifade aşağıdaki anlamlara gelir:

r"": Önceki kaçış dizilerini (escape sequences) etkisiz hale getiren bir hammadde dizesidir. Örneğin, "\n" bir yeni satır olarak değerlendirilirken, r"\n" sadece iki karakter olarak değerlendirilir.

\b: Bir kelime sınırını temsil eder. Bu, aramanın bir kelimenin başında yapılmasını sağlar.

S: Büyük "S" harfini arar.

\w+: "Kelime karakterlerinden" (harfler, rakamlar, alt çizgi) oluşan ve en az bir veya daha fazla tekrar bulunmasını ifade eder. Buradaki +, bir veya daha fazla uygun karakterin bulunması gerektiğini belirtir.

Special Sequences¶

Special sequences can be used in RegEx patterns:

\d: Matches any digit.

\D: Matches any non-digit.

\s: Matches any whitespace character.

\S: Matches any non-whitespace character.

\w: Matches any word character (alphanumeric and underscore).

\W: Matches any non-word character.

txt = "The rain in Spain 123"
digits = re.findall("\d", txt)
print("Digits found:", digits)  # Output: ['1', '2', '3']

Digits found: ['1', '2', '3']

Exercise:

Creating a password control example in Python can be done using regular expressions to validate passwords against specific rules.

Below is a simple implementation that checks if a password meets the following criteria:

Password Rules:

  • Minimum length of 8 characters.
  • At least one uppercase letter.
  • At least one lowercase letter.
  • At least one digit.
  • At least one special character (e.g., @, #, $, %, etc.).
import re

def validate_password(password):
    # Define the password rules using regular expressions
    if (len(password) < 8):
        return "Password must be at least 8 characters long."

    if not re.search(r"[A-Z]", password):
        return "Password must contain at least one uppercase letter."

    if not re.search(r"[a-z]", password):
        return "Password must contain at least one lowercase letter."

    if not re.search(r"\d", password):
        return "Password must contain at least one digit."

    if not re.search(r"[!@#$%^&*(),.?\":{}|<>]", password):
        return "Password must contain at least one special character."

    return "Password is valid!"

# Test cases
passwords = [
    "Password123!",    # Valid
    "password",        # Invalid (no uppercase, no digit, no special char)
    "PASSWORD123",     # Invalid (no lowercase, no special char)
    "Pass123",         # Invalid (too short)
    "Passw@rd",        # Valid
    "12345678",        # Invalid (no letters, no special char)
    "Pass!word"        # Valid
]

for pwd in passwords:
    print(f"Testing password: {pwd} -> {validate_password(pwd)}")

Testing password: Password123! -> Password is valid!
Testing password: password -> Password must contain at least one uppercase letter.
Testing password: PASSWORD123 -> Password must contain at least one lowercase letter.
Testing password: Pass123 -> Password must be at least 8 characters long.
Testing password: Passw@rd -> Password must contain at least one digit.
Testing password: 12345678 -> Password must contain at least one uppercase letter.
Testing password: Pass!word -> Password must contain at least one digit.
